One of the big implications in approaches that are based on CPPNs is, 
that complex patterns are generated without local interaction and other 
self-organizing principles.

In front of this context, I found these papers very interesting

Universality in the Evolution of Orientation Columns in the Visual Cortex
http://www.sciencemag.org/content/330/6007/1113.abstract

Using theoretical models to analyse neural development
http://www.nature.com/nrn/journal/v12/n6/full/nrn3031.html

The take home message of these and other papers is that - besides 
genetic prespecification - the function of a neural network ultimately 
emerges through self-organizing mechanisms between neurons.

I am wondering if there is an interpretation of CPPNs in HyperNEAT that 
allows to conclude that self-organization must not be explicitly modeled 
in these kinds of networks or (and this is my current opinion) whether 
these papers describe mechanisms that are so far missing in current 
implementations of CPPNs (such as HyperNEAT).

Best,
Martin

